<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n10144d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10144d">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10144d"> 144(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> sent a letter he at / first shot thought / postmortem / invoice</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">People don&apos;t notify deaths per post-card even in Luvaleland, and to send a huge ox is the African equivalent to sending black-edged mourning letter. A goat is a mere post-card. Here, then, is his chance to make vexatious delays, the preliminary trouble being how to get the relatives even to believe there is a death at all. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> &ldquo;To the much laughter you enjoyed for years when conversing with your late spouse, our legal cousin&mdash;total value, one goat.&rdquo; Not much to laugh at now. And so on and on, the <mark>post-mortem invoice</mark> runs, many a shameless (because nameless) item haggled over on a money basis [&hellip; <small> Daniel Crawford, <a name="DCTB" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#DCTB"><cite title="source">Thinking Black</cite></a> (1912) 134-5</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c01070d" href="c01all.htm#c01070d">VI.C.01:070(d)</a>, <a name="c01070e" href="c01all.htm#c01070e">VI.C.01:070(e)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
